[normal]Annex B: [bold]Russia case study[bold]This i
[normal]ndustry could not access a valu
[normal]able Russian market in beef and ruminant meat becau
[normal]se of 
[normal]a thirty-year long ban imposed due to BSE. 
[normal]Defra worked with British Embassy 
[normal]in 
[normal]Moscow and the Russian 
[normal]authorities
[normal] to 
[normal]remove this
[normal] ban. 
[normal]This required sustained
[normal] pressure at official and political level
[normal] over the last 30 years
[normal], 
[normal]accommodating
[normal] inspection visits of UK plants
[normal] and completing relevant paperwork required by the Russian authorities in
[normal]cluding lengthy questionnaires. 
[normal]This enabled trade to commence in ruminant meat after the 
[normal]ban 
[normal]was lifted in December 2012
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Further technical negotiation
[normal]s at Secretary of State and Chief  Veterinary Officer level in September this year extended the deal to offal, a priority for industry. I
[normal]ndustry sources estimate that beef and lamb exports to Russia over the next three years could be worth up to £100 milli
[normal]on, making it a very lucrative market for UK industry. Negotiations are now being progressed for export of live sheep. 
